INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1284,'This is the first version of the Zaurus to be sold as a consumer device.  Sharp sold it between TODO: when?  2000-2003 or so?\n\n{|\n| Form Factor || [[Portrait]]\n|-\n| Processor || 206 MHz Intel ARM\n|-\n| Screen || 320x240 TFT\n|-\n| RAM || 64 MB\n|-\n| Flash || 16 MB\n|-\n| Battery || 3.7V 950 mAh Li-Ion\n|-\n| A/C Adaptor || 5V 6.2W\n|-\n| Headphone Jack || Regular 1/8\" right??\n|-\n| Microphone || Mono, Built into headphone jack, requires an adaptor.\n|-\n| USB || Requires adaptor.  Can only act as a device, not as a host.\n|-\n| SD || 1 port\n|-\n| Compact Flash || 1 port\n|}\n\n== External Links ==\n\nDevice Profile at [http://www.linuxdevices.com/articles/AT2134869242.html Linux Devices]','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1285,'OpenZaurus is a Linux distribution that runs on the Sharp Zaurus PDA.\n\nSupported Zaurus models:\n\n* [[Collie|SL-5000/5500 - Collie]]\n* [[Poodle|SL-5600 - Poodle]]\n* [[Tosa|SL-6000 - Tosa]]\n* [[C7x0|C700/750/760/860 SL-7500 - c7x0]]\n* [[Akita|SL-C1000 - Akita]]\n* [[Spitz|SL-C3000/3100/3200 - Spitz]]\n\nDesktop Environments\n* [[GPE]]\n* [[Opie]]','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1286,'The Sharp Zaurus [[SL-5000]], [[Collie|SL-5500]], and [[Poodle|SL-5600]] all shared the same portrait form factor.  All other Zaurii use the [[Clamshell]] form factor.\n\nThe keyboard slides out from the bottom of the device and is inteded to be used with the thumbs.  The keys are tiny and recessed, which  can make it difficult to get used to at first.  With some practice, however, even people with large thumbs can use it productively.\n\n== 802.11 ==\n\nThis device does not have built-in 802.11 networking.  Most aftermarket CF-based adaptors work just fine.  Since they occupy the CF port, only the SD port can be used for additional storage.\n\nThere are two things to be aware of while buying an 802.11 adaptor:\n* Some adaptors have a wide antenna that will block the headphone jack and prevent you from removing and inserting the stylus.\n* Some older 802.11 CF adapters have very high power consumption, cutting your battery life by over 60%.\n\nKnown working 802.11 CF cards: DCF-660TX','utf-8');
