INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1392,'The Tosa family includes a single model, the SL-6000.  It has a [[Portrait]] form factor.\n\n[http://www.sharpusa.com/products/ModelLanding/0,1058,1255,00.html Sharp\'s Product Page]\n\nTosa is a breed of dog originating from the smallest of the four Japanese islands.  See [http://www.bulldoginformation.com/Tosa-inu.html this page] for a description and pictures.','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1393,'Sharp Zauruses come in two form factors: Portrait and [[Clamshell]].\n\nPortrait screens are taller than they are wide.  In addition, the device has a flip-up cover to protect the screen, rather than folding across its middle like a flip-phone.\n\nThe [[Collie]] and [[Poodle]] have a quarter-VGA 240x320 screens.  The [[Tosa]] has a full VGA 480x640 screen.\n\nThe keyboard slides out from the bottom of the device and is inteded to be used with the thumbs.  The keys are tiny and recessed, which  can make it difficult to get used to at first.  With some practice, however, even people with large thumbs can type somewhat productively.\n\n== 802.11 ==\n\nThis device does not have built-in 802.11 networking.  Most aftermarket CF-based adaptors work just fine.  Since they occupy the CF port, only the SD port can be used for additional storage.\n\nThere are two things to be aware of while buying an 802.11 adaptor:\n* Some adaptors have a wide antenna that will block the headphone jack and prevent you from removing and inserting the stylus.\n* Some older 802.11 CF adapters have very high power consumption, cutting your battery life by over 60%.\n\nKnown working 802.11 CF cards: DCF-660TX','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1394,'Sharp Zauruses come in two form factors: Portrait and [[Clamshell]].\n\nPortrait screens are taller than they are wide.  In addition, the device has a flip-up cover to protect the screen, rather than folding across its middle like a flip-phone.\n\nThe [[Collie]] and [[Poodle]] have a quarter-VGA 240x320 screens.  The [[Tosa]] has a full VGA 480x640 screen.\n\nThe keyboard slides out from the bottom of the device and is inteded to be used with the thumbs.  The keys are tiny and recessed, which  can make it difficult to get used to at first.  With some practice, however, even people with large thumbs can type somewhat productively.\n\n== 802.11 ==\n\nThe Tosa includes built-in 802.11 networking.  The Collie and Poodle require CF-based adaptors.\n\nThere are two things to be aware of while buying an 802.11 adaptor:\n* Some adaptors have a wide antenna that will block the headphone jack and prevent you from removing and inserting the stylus.\n* Some older 802.11 CF adapters have very high power consumption, cutting your battery life by over 60%.\n\nKnown working 802.11 CF cards: DCF-660TX\n\nTODO: maybe copy this section into the Collie and Poodle pages since it doesn\'t apply to the Tosa?','utf-8');
