INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1438,'This page describes how to maintain the content on this site.\n\n== Markup ==\n\nFor help on wiki markup, see Wikipedia\'s [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Editing help pages]].  You can experiment in [[Sandbox]].\n\nUse <code>&lt;nowiki&gt;</code> ... <code>&lt;/nowiki&gt;</code> to prevent characters from being interpreted as wiki markup.\n\n== Discussion ==\n\nSimply type your comment below the comment it is replying to, or last on the page.  Append <code><nowiki>~~~~</nowiki></code> to your comment to insert your name and the date.  There is no need to move one or two discussion comments to the discussion page.  However, once three comments are on a page, move the comments to the discussion page and insert a summary and a link to the discussion page into the original page.\n\n== Style ==\n\nSee the [[Style Guide]] for suggested terminology.\n\n== Notifications ==\n\nYou can have MediaWiki tell you whenever a page you are interested changes.  Just create an account and set up your preferences so that you can be sent an email whenever a page that you have previously edited is changed.  If that\'s too many notifications, you can also manually subscribe to individual pages.\n\nIf you want to watch every change on this site, just point your RSS feed reader to [http://openzaurus.berlios.de/wiki/index.php?title=Special:Recentchanges&feed=rss this url].','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1439,'When editing the [[MediaWiki:Sidebar]] you will see:\n\n  * navigation\n  ** mainpage-url|mainpage\n  * navigation(1)\n  ** mainpage-url(2)|mainpage(3)\n\nThe first line corresponds to [[MediaWiki:navigation]].  The content of that page will appear in the sidebar.\n\n  ** mainpage-url|mainpage\n\nThis is two things: mainpage-url and mainpage\n\n\"mainpage\" corresponds [[MediaWiki:mainpage]].  What is inside MediaWiki:mainpage\nis what will display in ths sidebar.\n\n\"mainpage-url\" corresponds [[MediaWiki:mainpage-url]].  What is inside\nMediaWiki:mainpage-url is where \"mainpage\" will send the user when\nthey click.  So if you change it to \"Sitemap\" it will send the user to\nthe page \"Sitemap\".','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1440,'This page describes how to maintain the content on this site.\n\n== Markup ==\n\nFor help on wiki markup, see Wikipedia\'s [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Editing help pages]].  You can experiment in [[Sandbox]].\n\nUse <code>&lt;nowiki&gt;</code> ... <code>&lt;/nowiki&gt;</code> to prevent characters from being interpreted as wiki markup.\n\n== Discussion ==\n\nSimply type your comment and append <code><nowiki>~~~~</nowiki></code> to insert your name and the date.  There is no need to move one or two insightful comments to the discussion page.  However, once a few comments are on a page, they should be moved to the discussion page.  Insert a summary and a link to the discussion page into the original page to tell people to look there.\n\nRants are fine, but they need to always go on discussion pages.\n\nWhen you create an account, you are assigned a personal page too.  We suggest using this page to express your opinions and findings.  If it\'s not too offensive, add a link to it from the [[Users]] page.\n\n== Style ==\n\nSee the [[Style Guide]] for suggested terminology.\n\n== Notifications ==\n\nYou can have MediaWiki tell you whenever a page you are interested changes.  Just create an account and set up your preferences so that you can be sent an email whenever a page that you have previously edited is changed.  If that\'s too many notifications, you can also manually subscribe to individual pages.\n\nIf you want to watch every change on this site, just point your RSS feed reader to [http://openzaurus.berlios.de/wiki/index.php?title=Special:Recentchanges&feed=rss this url].','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1441,'This page describes how to maintain the content on this site.\n\n== Markup ==\n\nFor help on wiki markup, see Wikipedia\'s [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Editing help pages]].  You can experiment in [[Sandbox]].\n\nUse <code>&lt;nowiki&gt;</code> ... <code>&lt;/nowiki&gt;</code> to prevent characters from being interpreted as wiki markup.\n\n== Discussion ==\n\nSimply type your comment and append <code><nowiki>~~~~</nowiki></code> to insert your name and the date.  There is no need to move one or two insightful comments to the discussion page.  However, once a few comments are on a page, they should be moved to the discussion page.  Insert a summary and a link to the discussion page into the original page to tell people to look there.\n\nRants are fine, but they need to always go on discussion pages.\n\nWhen you create an account, you are assigned a personal page too.  We suggest using this page to express your opinions and findings.  If it\'s not too offensive, add a link to it from the [[Users]] page.\n\n== Style ==\n\nSee the [[Style Guide]] for suggested terminology.\n\n== Notifications ==\n\nMediaWiki can email you whenever a page changes.  Just create an account and set up your watchlist preferences.  Your watchlist can include any page you edit, or just the pages you specify.\n\nIf you want to watch every change on this site (good for watching for spam), just point your RSS feed reader to [http://openzaurus.berlios.de/wiki/index.php?title=Special:Recentchanges&feed=rss this url].','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1442,'This page contains some guidelines to use when adding documentation to this site.  As long as pages follow these rules, we can maintain some consistency across the site.\n\n* It\'s \"Zauruses\", not Zaurii or other odd pluralizations.\n* Always use [[DogName]]s unless you need to make a distinction of devices in the same family.  \'\'The [[Collie]] and [[Poodle]] are Portrait Zauruses.  Of these devices, the [[SL-5000]] and [[SL-5600]] have 32 MB of RAM while the [[SL-5500]] has 64 MB.\'\'\n* [[DogName]]s and [[ModelName]]s always redirect to the appropriate page.\n: Well... it\'s not obvious to do that since dognames are not wiki words (mix of upper/lower case)... so not specially easy to type when writing inn the wiki... --[[User:OlivierBerger|OlivierBerger]] 13:14, 13 April 2006 (BST)\n: MediaWiki doesn\'t really use WikiWords anyway.  I\'m afraid you\'ll have to use <nowiki>[[brackets]]</nowiki> for each link. [[User:Bronson|Bronson]] 18:48, 13 April 2006 (BST)\n* \"Zaurus\" is always capitalized.\n\nUse proper namespaces:\n\n* /HowTo/USB_Networking\n* /HowTo/Passwordless_SSH\n* /HowTo/SomethingOther\n\n* /Docs/Something\n\nUse language code after section name:\n\n* /HowTo/DE/USB_Netzwerk\n* /HowTo/FR/Le_réseau_par_USB','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1443,'This page contains some guidelines to use when adding documentation to this site.  As long as pages follow these rules, we can maintain some consistency across the site.\n\n* It\'s \"Zauruses\", not Zaurii or other odd pluralizations.\n* Always use [[DogName]]s unless you need to make a distinction of devices in the same family.  \'\'The [[Collie]] and [[Poodle]] are Portrait Zauruses.  Of these devices, the [[SL-5000]] and [[SL-5600]] have 32 MB of RAM while the [[SL-5500]] has 64 MB.\'\'\n* [[DogName]]s and [[ModelName]]s always redirect to the appropriate page.\n: Well... it\'s not obvious to do that since dognames are not wiki words (mix of upper/lower case)... so not specially easy to type when writing inn the wiki... --[[User:OlivierBerger|OlivierBerger]] 13:14, 13 April 2006 (BST)\n: MediaWiki doesn\'t really use WikiWords anyway.  I\'m afraid you\'ll have to use <nowiki>[[brackets]]</nowiki> for each link. [[User:Bronson|Bronson]] 18:48, 13 April 2006 (BST)\n* \"Zaurus\" is always capitalized.\n\nUse proper namespaces:\n\n* /HowTo/USB_Networking\n* /HowTo/Passwordless_SSH\n* /HowTo/SomethingOther\n\n* /Docs/Something\n\nUse language code after section name:\n\n* /HowTo/DE/USB_Netzwerk\n* /HowTo/FR/Le_réseau_par_USB\n\nThe pages on this wiki should be used for objective presentation of information.  Rants are encouraged -- within reason -- but they must be confined to the discussion pages or your personal page.  You must create an account to have a personal page.','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1444,'== Equipment ==\n\n* Zaurus [[SL-5500]] obtained through the [http://www.linuxdevices.com/news/NS4241298322.html Home Shopping Network blowout].\n* D-Link DCF-660W 802.11 Compact Flash card.\n* 256 MB SanDisk SD Card\n\n== Hardware Thoughts == \n\nI normally run the 64/0 image.  The 16 MB flash in the device is way too small, but I don\'t like trying to decide where to install apps, and having them disappear when I eject the SD card.  Also, my SD card is damned slow.  I wish wish WISH this device had 32 MB flash.\n\nThe screen is too damn narrow for browsing the web.  It\'s barely liveable if you rotate the screen and use the device sideways.  I don\'t care how high the screen is, just give me width!\n\n== GPE Thoughts ==\n\nOpie is a far more polished environment.  That said, I like GPE better.  GPE feels more like it\'s more a part of the Linux desktop.  Opie feels somewhat like a one-off hack.  That\'s just my opinion, of course.\n\nSome issues:\n\n* Why does a tap-longtap scroll a scroll bar to the extreme end?  This makes it damned hard to scroll line-by-line.  It\'s lika tap-tap-tap tap-damn where was I?  Its painful.  If I want to go to the bottom, I\'ll just drag the scroll bar thumb thank you very much.  (this awful behavior smells intentional because it seems like the device would have to go out of its way to do this...)\n\n* It\'s really strange that there\'s no active task switcher. I would expect a submenu in the Start menu or a task menu applet. Or both. Instead, you can sometimes click on the window\'s title bar.  How am I supposed to discover that??\n\n* Window titlebars take up a lot of room and really don\'t offer much functionality that I can tell.  The panel, on the other hand, is always overflowing with icons.  How about allowing us to place applets on the outsides of the window title bar?\n\n* interactive-help: useless, hopeless, a waste of space!\n** useless: couldn\'t find anything that actually offered help\n** hopeless: there is no way you\'re going to add help for everything that the user can click on.  It\'s much better\n** waste of space: the panel on a portrait Z doesn\'t have much room for icons.  And certainly it has no room for an icon this useless.\n** What\'s worse than not having a help button?  Having a help button that is totally and utterly unhelpful.\n\n* I\'ve seen a tiny analog clock in GPE screenshots.  Where can I obtain this?  Solve the width and rotation issues in one blow.\n\n* gpe-aerial:\n** Should take over the function of the wireless monitor.\n** Should display your current settings when you click on it\n** Shoulw have an \"associate with other networks\" button that would bring up the network switcher.\n\n* Panel doesn\'t handle rotation very well.  Especially the alarm clock changing its size.  Panel Manager should allow you to add and remove panel apps too.\n: Remove: just add an X right below the ^ and v arrows.\n: Add: make another list of the apps available to add.\n\n* Should add a battery graph to the CPU/mem monitor.  Ideally, whould make configurable which bars are shown in the panel.  Then the window that comes up would show all the bars, with labels.\n** network bandwidth\n** Disk space\n** temperature?\n\n* Package Manager\n** Should show progress monitor in dialog on startup.\n** Should quit entirely if startup window is closed.  As it is, it looks like it should work... but quits the minute you click on something.\n** Should display a description of the pack','utf-8');
