INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1819,'Here are some useful instructions about video encoding and playback avaliable from the pdaXrom site:\n\nhttp://mail.pdaxrom.org/node/63\n\nI have found the following page useful as well:\n\nhttp://www.zeb.uklinux.net/encoding.html\n\nHere is a script for playing mpegs/mp3s with mplayer (using the mad libs and the framebuffer):\n<br/>\n\n<nowiki>\n#!/bin/sh\n</nowiki>\n<br/>\nmplayer -quiet -vo fbdev -ac mad -framedrop -fs $1\n<br/>\n\nHere is the script I use for playing ogg/ogm files:\n<br/>\n\n<nowiki>\n#!/bin/sh\n</nowiki>\n<br/>\nmplayer -quiet -vo fbdev -framedrop -fs $1\n\n\n\n\n== Encoding and Playing Video for C7×0 Devices ==\nCopied from http://openzaurus.org/wordpress/howto/encoding-and-playing-video-for-c7x0-devices/\n\nMay 4th, 2005 by XorA\n\nUPDATED 06/07/2005\n\nThe golden version of mplayer for the c7×0 devices currently is mplayer-atty_1.1.5 as found in OE. You should build a copy of this or find someone that has it built.\n\nTo play videos optimally (at 30 fps with no drops on 400Mhz clamshells) they should be resized to 320×240 using DivX and mp3 (ogg is possible but mencoder doesnt do ogg). Here is the script I use to encode my videos.\n\n#!/bin/sh\n\nOUTFILE=$1\necho \"Outputting to $OUTFILE\"\nshift\n\nmencoder \"$@\" -ovc lavc -lavcopts vcodec=mpeg4:vbitrate=300:vpass=1 \\\n -lameopts cbr:br=64:mode=3 -vf scale=320:240,rotate=1 -oac mp3lame -o $OUTFILE\nmencoder \"$@\" -ovc lavc -lavcopts vcodec=mpeg4:vbitrate=300:vpass=2 \\\n -lameopts cbr:br=64:mode=3 -vf scale=320:240,rotate=1 -oac mp3lame -o $OUTFILE\n\nRun this as encode blah-output.avi blah-input.avi, you will get a nicely resized and rotated DivX movie. I rotate on desktop as overlay on C7×0 is always in portrait and it wastes valuable CPU to rotate on the Z itself.\n\nRecent changes to mplayer-atty mean you no longer need to switch out of X11/Opie in order to play videos. This means the playing command has got a lot simpler.\n\n#! /bin/sh\n\n# next line depends on kernel version\necho 1 >/sys/class/graphics/fb0/driver/w100fb/fastpllclk\necho 1 >/sys/class/graphics/fb0/device/fastpllclk\n\nmplayer -vo w100 -ac mad -ao oss -framedrop -really-quiet -fs $@\n\nI find this script will happilly play the movies I have resized at full speed on a C860 device.\n\nThere is a small bit of corruption on left hand side of my screen, Im not sure what causes this, but its hardly noticable.','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1820,'This describes how to install OpenZaurus on the [[Collie]].\n\n=== Selecting a zImage file ===\n\nThe zImage file contains the Linux kernel used in OpenZaurus.\n\nThere are numerous choices of zImage and initrd files available for OpenZaurus. They will be named as follows:\n\n   zImage-collie-Xmemory-Ystorage.bin\n\nWhere X is the amount of RAM devoted to system memory, and Y (if applicable) is the amount of RAM devoted to storage space. X+Y should equal 64MB for SL5500 owners and 32MB for SL5000D owners. Note that if you have an SL-5000D, you should choose the zImage-collie-32-0 image unless you know what you are doing, because the 24-8 image doesn’t leave enough memory to run GPE or Opie very well.\n\nDownload the zImage from http://openzaurus.org/wordpress/downloads/; you will find them in the “sl5000,sl5500″ directory, and rename it to just “zImage”.\n\n=== Download the initrd ===\n\nThe initrd.bin contains the basic filesystem structure and default programs for OpenZaurus.\n\nThere are three possible initrds: opie-image contains Opie, the QT/Embedded based graphical system (which is most like the original Sharp ROM), gpe-image contains the GPE Palmtop Environment, and the bootstrap file is more for basing distributions upon and contains no graphical system. If you don’t know which you want then you probably want Opie.\n\nDownload your choice of initrd image (opie-image, gpe-image or bootstrap image) from the Downloads link to the left (in the “sl5000,5500″ directory), and rename it to “initrd.bin”.\n\n=== Place both files on your CompactFlash card ===\n\nYou will need a CompactFlash card (not an SD card; CF cards are the largish square ones that fit in the top slot of the Zaurus) with at least 16MB of space available.\n\nBe sure, as described above, to rename your chosen zImage file (zImage-collie-Xmemory-Ystorage.bin) to just “zImage” and make sure your chosen initrd is named “initrd.bin”. Transfer both files to your CompactFlash card. If you don’t have a compactflash reader, you can copy the files to your Zaurus (via Qtopia Desktop, scp, ftp, or whatever method you use for file transfer) and move them onto the CompactFlash card.\n\nMake sure your files are in the root directory of your flash card. For example, if you copied the files to your Zaurus they will be in /mnt/cf/Documents/Applications/octet-stream. They should be moved to /mnt/cf (use the file manager for this or use the console).\n\nNote: Do NOT attempt to flash your Zaurus with a ext2 formatted CF card. Your CF card MUST be formatted as fat16 (mkfs.vfat -F 16 /dev/hda1). All CF cards come formatted as vfat when you buy them, so unless you have reformatted your CF card, there is nothing to worry about.\n\n=== Flash ===\n\nFlashing is the process of replacing the basic information and programs on the Zaurus with new ones (in this case, the kernel and root filesystem). It will remove all files from your Zaurus except those on SD or CompactFlash. This means programs not installed on SD or CompactFlash will not run after the upgrade.\n\n# Make sure all your data is backed up!\n# Insert the card with the files into the Zaurus or confirm that they have both transferred completely.\n# Make sure that the AC adapter is connected to the Zaurus and is plugged in.\n# Move the switch below the battery compartment to “REPLACE BATTERY.” Open the battery compartment lid. Make sure you DO NOT take the battery out.\n# Hold down the “C” and “D” keys on the Zaurus’ keyboard and press the “FULL RESET” button located on the lower-right side of the battery compartment.\n# Both the power and mail lights on the Zaurus should light up and stay lit up once you let go. If they do not light up, try again - you didn’t press the combination correctly, or you may not have the power cable plugged into the Zaurus. If they light up and then turn off after about a second, the zImage and initrd.bin files were not found. Make sure your card is formatted with vfat and the files are in the root of the flash card (not in any subdirectories). If the lights flash on and off, then this indicates a failure; something went wrong. (What went wrong is difficult to diagnose; try running through this process again and checking all the steps, or using a different CF card).\n# Do not touch anything when the Zaurus is flashing! Do not unplug the power. The flash should take between 3 and 12 minutes for a standard CF card, longer if flashing from a microdrive.\n# After the green LED goes out, push the “FULL RESET” button in the lower-right side of the battery compartment.\n# Replace the battery compartment lid and slide the battery replacement switch to “NORMAL OPERATION.”\n\n=== Reboot ===\n\nTurn on your Zaurus!\n\nBooting up OpenZaurus for the first time may take a while. So please be patient. Once it boots, you should have a fully working Zaurus running your new image.\n\nHave fun!\n\n\n=== Origin ===\n\nThese instructions were copied from\nhttp://openzaurus.org/wordpress/installation/sl-50005500/\n\n=== Special Note on OZ on the Collie Platform ===\n\nThese instructions should include a method for moving your root filesystem to an SD card of sufficient size to accomodate an OZ install.  The current version of OZ is essentially broken out of the box on Collie because you cannot do even an ipkg update on it without running out of room on root.  This doesn\'t mean you can\'t use OZ on a Collie, but there is an additional, nontrivial step to take before your system is usable.','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1821,'Bei diesem HowTo habe ich mit einem Opie OZ Image angefangen. Warscheinlich können Sie auch mit einem GPE System beginnen, aber diese Anleitung geht von Opie aus.\n\nFlashen Sie Ihren Zaurus mit dem Opie Image. Vorzugsweise mit einem Kernel der Ihnen das meiste RAM beschert (Anm.d.Übers.: Trifft nur auf SL5000/SL5500 zu). Ich habe das 64-0 Image für meinen Collie genommen.\n\nKopieren Sie Ihr Root-Dateisystem (kurz: RootFS) auf eine SD Karte, als Dateisystem habe ich ext2 verwendet. Zur Hilfe habe ich diese [http://openzaurus.org/wordpress/go.php?http://www.openzaurus.org/oz_website/faq/faq?id=192 Anleitung (Eng.)] genommen. Wenn Sie Ihr RootFS nicht auf SD verschieben möchten, können Sie GPE auch auf CF oder SD installieren und mittels ipkg-link in Ihr RootFS einbinden.\n\nÄndern Sie Opie um auf VT3 zu starten. Das machen Sie, indem Sie die Datei /etc/init.d/opie editieren und alle Vorkommen von “-terminal 2″ in “-terminal 3″ ändern.\n\nStarten Sie Opie nun neu damit die Änderung wirksam wird. Ein kompletter Reboot ist wohl der einfachste Weg, auch wenn er nicht wirklich nötig ist. Sie können alternativ über das OPIE-Menü auch auf das erste Virtual Terminal wechseln und mit<br>\n/etc/init.d/opie restart<br>\nOPIE neustarten.\n\nEditieren Sie die IPKG Quellen in /etc/ipkg.conf und fügen Sie die Pfade für die GPE Feeds hinzu:\n\nsrc e http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/e/\n\nsrc gnome http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/gnome/\n\nsrc upgrades http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/upgrades/\n\nsrc upgrades2 http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/upgrades/\n\nsrc devel http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/devel/\n\nsrc kernel http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/kernel/\n\nsrc base http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/base/\n\nsrc libs http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/libs/\n\nsrc console http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/console/\n\nsrc opie http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/opie/\n\nsrc unknown http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/unknown/\n\nsrc gpe http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/gpe/\n\nsrc x11 http://openzaurus.org/official/unstable/3.5.3/feed/x11/\n\nJetzt ist es an der Zeit die IPKG Paketdaten mit der neuen Liste zu aktualisieren:\n\nipkg update\n\nInstallieren Sie nun die GPE Pakete. Aufgrund von fehlerhaften Abhängigkeiten (Dependencies) müssen Sie den “-force-depends” Parameter bei ipkg benutzen.\n\nAusserdem müssen Sie libcairo1 manuell installieren, da es für dieses Pakte keine korrekte Abhängigkeit gibt. Sie müssen ebenfalls darauf achten, dass Sie den richtigen X-Server für Ihren Zaurus auswählen, je nach Zaurus kann sich dieser unterscheiden.\n\nipkg install libcairo1\nipkg install -force-depends xserver-kdrive-fbdev\nipkg install -force-depends gpe-base-depends gpe-task-base gpe-task-settings\n\nSie müssen noch “bluez-utils-nodbus” entfernen um gpe-task-base installieren zu können, oder alternativ “ipkg install -force-overwrite bluez-utils-nodbus. Die korrekte Lösung für dieses Problem kenne ich leider nicht, aber ich glaube ich hatte -force-overwrite benutzt.\n\nFalls während der Installation Fehler auftraten versuchen Sie einfach erneut “darüber” zu installieren. Zu diesem Zeitpunkt sollte GPE schon eigenständig starten nach einem Reboot falls alles funktioniert hat.\n\nSie haben nun sowohl Opie, als auch GPE auf Ihrem Zaurus, viel Spass damit!\n\nEs gibt noch ein paar Kleinigkeiten die ich geändert habe um mit GPE besser arbeiten zu können. Zunächst ein Script um einfach von GPE nach Opie umzuschalten:\n\nSpeichern Sie folgendes in “/gotoopie.sh”:\n\n#!/bin/sh\nchvt 3\n\nNun erstellen wir ein Desktop Icon für GPE. Fügen Sie folgende Zeilen in die Datei\n\n/usr/share/applications/goto-opie.desktop ein:\n\n[Desktop Entry]<br>\nName=Zu Opie wechseln<br>\nComment=Zu Opie wechseln<br>\nExec=/gotoopie.sh<br>\nTerminal=0<br>\nType=Application<br>\nIcon=/opt/QtPalmtop/pics/logo/opielogo.png<br>\nCategories=Utility;GPE<br>\nStartupNotify=False<br>\n\nWechseln sie in die “Utilities” Gruppe [FIXME: Wie heist das auf deutsch?] und Sie sollten dort ein neues Icon finden.\n\nIch habe ausserdem ein “Suspend” Icon hinzugefügt, da GPE keins mitliefert:\n\n#!/bin/sh\napm -s\n\nDies könnte allerdings einen C-Serie Zaurus abstürzen lassen. Wenn dem so ist, verwenden Sie einfach folgendes:\n\n#!/bin/sh\necho 1 > /proc/sys/pm/suspend\n\nNun erstellen wir noch ein neues Icon mit der Datei “/usr/share/applications/suspend.desktop”:\n\n[Desktop Entry]\nName=Suspend<br>\nComment=Suspend<br>\nExec=/suspend.sh<br>\nTerminal=0<br>\nType=Application<br>\nIcon=gpe-config-sleep.png<br>\nCategories=Utility;GPE<br>\nStartupNotify=False<br>\n\nEs ist möglich, dass Sie sich aus GPE ausloggen müssen damit die neuen Icons sichbar werden.','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1822,'Sharp Zauruses come in two form factors: Portrait and [[Clamshell]].\n\nPortrait screens are taller than they are wide.  In addition, the device has a flip-up cover to protect the screen, rather than folding across its middle like a flip-phone.\n\nThe [[Collie]] and [[Poodle]] have a quarter-VGA 240x320 screens.  The [[Tosa]] has a full VGA 480x640 screen.\n\nThe keyboard slides out from the bottom of the device and is intended to be used with the thumbs.  The keys are tiny and recessed, which  can make it difficult to get used to at first.  With some practice, however, even people with large thumbs can type somewhat productively.\n\n== 802.11 ==\n\nThe Tosa includes built-in 802.11 networking.  The Collie and Poodle require CF-based adaptors.\n\nThere are two things to be aware of while buying an 802.11 adaptor:\n* Some adaptors have a wide antenna that will block the headphone jack and prevent you from removing and inserting the stylus.\n* Some older 802.11 CF adapters have very high power consumption, cutting your battery life by over 60%.\n\nKnown working 802.11 CF cards: DCF-660TX\n\nTODO: maybe copy this section into the Collie and Poodle pages since it doesn\'t apply to the Tosa?','utf-8');
