INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1894,'\'\'\'Oliver Elphick\'\'\'\n\n\'\'\'Equipment\'\'\': Zaurus SL-C3100, SL-C3200\n\nThe C3200 currently has Sharp\'s O/S on it.  The C3100 is a testbed for OpenZaurus.\n\n\'\'\'Project\'\'\': Use for van drivers visiting various shops','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1895,'= First experiences with OpenZaurus =\n\nI used 3.5.4.1-rc4, \'\'\'spitz\'\'\' version and selected the opie image.\n\nI followed the instructions at [http://www.oesf.org/index.php?title=C3100_OpenZaurus].\n\nThere were no problems in repartitioning the C3100 and installing OpenZaurus on it. I got as far as making filesystems.  In order to make the VFAT filesystem on <tt>/dev/hda3</tt> \'\'(why does this need to be VFAT?)\'\' I had first to install \'\'\'dosfstools\'\'\', which in turn needed USB networking.\n\n\n== USB networking ==\n\nI had already got USB networking with the native Zaurus O/S.  This set up does not work with OpenZaurus.\n\nFor the USB device to be recognised by the host computer, I had to load the \'\'\'usbnet\'\'\' and \'\'\'g_ether\'\'\' modules.  With these present, the following line was produced by <tt>lsusb</tt> on the host:\n\n <tt>Bus 003 Device 016: ID 0525:a4a2 Netchip Technology, Inc. Linux-USB Ethernet/RNDIS Gadget</tt>\n\nThe USB identity is <tt>0525:a4a2</tt> as opposed to <tt>04dd:9031</tt> for the native Zaurus O/S.\n\nI also needed to set up <tt>/etc/resolv.conf</tt> with the address of a nameserver.\n\nFinally I had to set up a default route; the gateway line in <tt>/etc/network/interfaces</tt> does not cause this to happen automatically:\n\n <tt>route add default gw 192.168.129.200</tt>\n\n\n== Continuing installation ==\n\nAt this point I was able to run \n\n <tt>ipkg update; ipkg upgrade; ipkg install dosfstools</tt>\n\nSince this was such a new release, nothing was upgraded.  I was now able to make the VFAT filesystem on <tt>/dev/hda3</tt>.\n\n\'\'\'Problem\'\'\': on installation, root does not have a home directory; <tt>/etc/passwd</tt> sets it to <tt>/home/root</tt>, but this directory does not exist.  I created it.\n\nI used <tt>adduser</tt> to create a personal login.\n\nI set a root password and set the system date using <tt>date -u</tt>.  The system does not seem to recognise <tt>Europe/London</tt> as a timezone.  It does recognise <tt>GMT1</tt>.\n\n== Current position ==\n\nI have a basic Linux system running.  Although I loaded the opie tar image and chose <tt>1. Normal boot</tt> from the altboot prompt, I do not get a graphical system; there is no reference to X in /etc/inittab and no indication of how to get it running.\n\nClearly, more research is needed...','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1896,'= First experiences with OpenZaurus =\n\nThe object of this narrative is to describe the experiences of someone coming to OpenZaurus for the first time.  Inevitably, a new user will come with assumptions that differ from those of the project\'s developers and his experiences of the installation may reveal things that need to be documented for all users.\n\nTherefore, I am trying to recount what I did so as to reveal the assumptions I started with.  I hope this will help to refine the installation documnetation.\n\nI have about 18 years experience of Unix; 12 of Linux.  I am a Debian developer and familiar with Debian\'s filesystem layout.  I am experienced with programming in BASIC, bash shell script, C, awk, sed, Perl, Eiffel and lately C++.  I once did some Z80 assembler programming.\n\n== System ==\n\nI set out to installOpenZaurus on a SL-C3100, which was previously running Zaurus\' native O/S.  My host computer runs Debian unstable.  It has \'\'\'dbus\'\'\' and \'\'\'hal\'\'\' installed rather than \'\'\'hotplug\'\'\'.\n\nI used 3.5.4.1-rc4, \'\'\'spitz\'\'\' version and selected the opie image, since the application I have already written is developed with Qtopia.\n\nI followed the instructions at [http://www.oesf.org/index.php?title=C3100_OpenZaurus].\n\nThere were no problems in repartitioning the C3100 and installing OpenZaurus on it. I got as far as making filesystems.  In order to make the VFAT filesystem on <tt>/dev/hda3</tt> \'\'(why does this need to be VFAT?)\'\' I had first to install \'\'\'dosfstools\'\'\', which in turn needed USB networking.\n\n== USB networking ==\n\nI had already got USB networking with the native Zaurus O/S.  This set-up does not work with OpenZaurus.\n\nFor the USB device to be recognised by the host computer, I had to load the \'\'\'usbnet\'\'\' and \'\'\'g_ether\'\'\' modules.  With these present, the following line was produced by <tt>lsusb</tt> on the host:\n\n <tt>Bus 003 Device 016: ID 0525:a4a2 Netchip Technology, Inc. Linux-USB Ethernet/RNDIS Gadget</tt>\n\nThe USB identity is <tt>0525:a4a2</tt> as opposed to <tt>04dd:9031</tt> for the native Zaurus O/S.  This meant changes to the hal configuration in <tt>/etc/hal/fdi/information/zaurus.fdi</tt> on the server, so that it would create the network interface <tt>usb0</tt>.\n\nI also needed to set up <tt>/etc/resolv.conf</tt> on the Z|aurus with the address of a nameserver.\n\nFinally I had to set up a default route; the gateway line in <tt>/etc/network/interfaces</tt> does not cause this to happen automatically:\n\n <tt>route add default gw 192.168.129.200</tt>\n\n== Continuing installation ==\n\nAt this point I was able to run \n\n <tt>ipkg update; ipkg upgrade; ipkg install dosfstools</tt>\n\nSince this was such a new release, nothing was upgraded.  I was now able to make the VFAT filesystem on <tt>/dev/hda3</tt>.\n\n\'\'\'Problem\'\'\': on installation, root does not have a home directory; <tt>/etc/passwd</tt> sets it to <tt>/home/root</tt>, but this directory does not exist.  I created it.\n\nI used <tt>adduser</tt> to create a personal login.\n\nI set a root password and set the system date using <tt>date -u</tt>.  The system does not seem to recognise <tt>Europe/London</tt> as a timezone.  It does recognise <tt>GMT1</tt>.\n\n== Installing Opie ==\n\nI now had a basic Linux system running.  Although I had loaded the opie tar image and chose <tt>1. Normal boot</tt> from the altboot prompt, I was not getting a graphical system; there is no reference to X in /etc/inittab and no indication of how to get it running.\n\nClearly, more research was needed...\n\nI used <tt>find</tt> to search the file system for files whose names include <tt>\'opie\'</tt>; there were almost none, so I concluded that I needed to install opie packages.  I searched for the main Opie site and discovered instructions for loading Familiar on an Ipaq; it seemed that these were inappropriate for a Zaurus and that I had to install specific packages.  So I did\n\n <tt>ipkg list | grep opie | sort -u | more</tt>\n\nto get a list of all opie-related packages; I had hoped to find a single \'\'\'task-opie\'\'\' package that would have installed as dependencies everything relevant, but there did not seem to be such a package.  So I installed some packages that looked as though they would be needed by my end users (we don\'t want our van drivers to be playing games on the Zaurus when they should be selling!)\n\nAt this point I switched to using ssh from my host computer; this made it a lot easier to read the screen and also to cut and paste between windows; typing on the Zaurus keyboard is a relatively slow job, particularly if you have big fingers!\n\nI continued by installing all the \'\'\'task-opie-*\'\'\' packages except for \'\'\'task-opie-games\'\'\' and \'\'\'task-opie-extra-games\'\'\'.  This had the desired effect of loading lots of opie packages.  However, something caused the main Zaurus console to go blank and unresponsive and I had to reboot it.  On rebooting, Opie started up, but with the screen oriented vertically; it did not respond to physically changing the screen position.  Set up Opie in response to prompts - the system is running as root, as shown by the prompt in a console, but it never asked for the root password, although opie-login is installed.\n\n...to be continued...','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1897,'To install OpenZaurus: [[Collie/Install]]\n\nRuns the [[KernelInfo24|Linux 2.4 kernel]].\n\nThe Collie was the first Zaurus to be sold as a consumer device. The Collie family consists of two models, the SL-5000D, announced in late 2001,  and the SL-5500, announced in mid-2002.  Because of its limited memory, the SL-5000D was intended to be used mostly by developers to prepare software for the soon-to-be released SL-5500.  The D stood for \"developer\".\n\nThe SL-5500G is version of the SL-5500 targeted for the German market.  The only differences between the 5500 and the 5500G are the graphical markings on the unit:\n* The Z and Y keys are transposed (the German device has a QWERTZ keyboard).\n* Right Shift is AltGr.\n\nOn a Collie it is possible to enter the diagnostics system. The process is similar to flashing a new ROM. \n* Power off and open the battery cover\n* hold G and D (you can also try D and P)\n* press reset with stylus\n\nThe diag screen will help you test every aspect of the zaurus hardware including if your CF slot is working or not.\n\nTo exit: \n* Navigate to screen 3/4 (using left/right buttons)\n* Select \"Clear Diagnostic Flag\" and press \"Ok\"\n* Reset the device by pressing the full reset button at the back of the unit. \n\n\nThe [[Poodle]] appears similar to the Collie but it has a different CPU and memory configuration.  The [[Tosa]] is a significantly upgraded device, with a larger screen, more memory, and built-in 802.11.\n\n== Collie Specifications ==\n\n{|\n| Form Factor || [[Portrait]]\n|-\n| Processor || 206 MHz Intel ARM\n|-\n| Screen || 320x240 TFT reflective\n|-\n| RAM || 32 MB (5000), 64 MB (5500)\n|-\n| Flash || 16 MB\n|-\n| Battery || 3.7V 950 mAh Li-Ion\n|-\n| A/C Adaptor || 5V 6.2W\n|-\n| Headphone Jack || Regular 1/8\"\n|-\n| Microphone || Mono, Built into headphone jack, requires an adaptor.\n|-\n| USB || Requires adaptor.  Can only act as a device, not as a host.\n|-\n| SD || 1 port\n|-\n| Compact Flash || 1 port\n|}\n\n== External Links ==\n\nDevice Profile at [http://www.linuxdevices.com/articles/AT2134869242.html Linux Devices]','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1898,'=Status=\n\nKernel 2.4 on Zaurus is nightmare to support... So noone want to do it. It\'s quality is so low that it is called 2.4-crapix by most of devels.\n\nAnd it need gcc 2.95 which is not available in [[OpenEmbedded]] (and will never be as noone is so crazy to use it for anything other then compiling 2.4 Zaurus kernels).\n\n=Patches=\n\nWe use 2.4.18 with amount of misc patches:\n\n* many fixes\n* Wireless Extensions upto v18 - needed for WPA\n* latest available BlueTooth patches\n* detailed battery status\n* OpenSwan\n* some IrDa fixes\n* some backports\n\n=Models=\nCurrently only few Zauruses supported by OpenZaurus use 2.4 kernel:\n\n* [[Collie]]\n* [[Poodle]]\n* [[Tosa]]\n\n=Why still 2.4?=\n\nThere are a number of reasons why we still use 2.4 kernel. Most important are:\n\n* lack of kernel hackers which will work on getting 2.6 working\n* The Locomo chip in [[Collie]], abused by Sharp to poorly handle SD, is totally undocumented.','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1899,'OpenEmbedded is a build system used to build OpenZaurus 3.5.x releases.\n\n[http://www.openembedded.org/ Website]','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1900,'=History=\n\nWhen [[Collie]] was released it used 2.4.6 kernel (SharpROM 2.x and OpenZaurus 3.2). With SharpROM 3.x 2.4.18 was released - we stlll use it (heavily patched) in OpenZaurus.\n\n[[Poodle]] and [[Tosa]] also was released with 2.4.18 kernels and they are still in use (both machines and kernel).\n\n[[Spitz]] was released with 2.4.20 kernel which also was used for rest of Cxx00: [[Akita]], [[Borzoi]] and [[Terrier]]. We tried to use it with 3.5.3 and 3.5.4-RC but this kernel is much worse then 2.4.18 so we decided to not release 3.5.4 with it.\n\n=2.6 work=\n\nFirst Zaurus which booted 2.6 kernel was [[Collie]]. Work was done by John Lenz - he also started work on [[Poodle]] support. Some time after Richard \'RP\' Purdie started work on getting 2.6 working on [[C7x0]] family. Also work was started on getting 2.6 working on [[Tosa]] - Dirk \'do13\' Opfer was the first. With Cxx00 release list of machines with 2.6 kernel booting was increased - Alexander Wykes started work on [[Spitz]].\n\n=Current situation=\n\nCurrently we have 2.6.16 working nice on all clamshells, Tosa support is progressing, Poodle and Collie are partially working.\n\n=More info=\n[[KernelInfo26|Kernel 2.6 Information]]\n\n[[KernelInfo24|Kernel 2.4 Information]]','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1901,'=History=\n\nWhen [[Collie]] was released it used 2.4.6 kernel (SharpROM 2.x and OpenZaurus 3.2). With SharpROM 3.x 2.4.18 was released - we stlll use it (heavily patched) in OpenZaurus.\n\n[[Poodle]] and [[Tosa]] also was released with 2.4.18 kernels and they are still in use (both machines and kernel).\n\n[[Spitz]] was released with 2.4.20 kernel which also was used for rest of Cxx00: [[Akita]], [[Borzoi]] and [[Terrier]]. We tried to use it with 3.5.3 and 3.5.4-RC but this kernel is much worse then 2.4.18 so we decided to not release 3.5.4 with it.\n\n=2.6 work=\n\nFirst Zaurus which booted 2.6 kernel was [[Collie]]. Work was done by John Lenz - he also started work on [[Poodle]] support. Some time after Richard \'RP\' Purdie started work on getting 2.6 working on [[C7x0]] family. Also work was started on getting 2.6 working on [[Tosa]] - Dirk \'do13\' Opfer was the first. With Cxx00 release list of machines with 2.6 kernel booting was increased - Alexander Wykes started work on [[Spitz]].\n\n=Current situation=\n\nCurrently we have 2.6.16 working nice on all clamshells, Tosa support is progressing, Poodle and Collie are partially working.\n\nRichard Purdie is official Zaurus maintainer in Linux 2.6 kernel. He works on clamshells support and recently also on [[Poodle]]. [http://rpsys.net/openzaurus/ Status website]\n\nPavel Machek works on [[Collie]] support - his [http://kernel.org/git/?p=linux/kernel/git/pavel/zaurus.git;a=summary git tree is available].\n\nDirk Opfer works on [[Tosa]] support with Chris Humbert. [http://www.do13.de/openzaurus/ Status website].\n\nKernel can be built using [[OpenEmbedded]] - it\'s \"linux-openzaurus\".\n\n=More info=\n[[KernelInfo26|Kernel 2.6 Information]]\n\n[[KernelInfo24|Kernel 2.4 Information]]','utf-8');
INSERT INTO mw_text VALUES (1902,'= First experiences with OpenZaurus =\n\nThe object of this narrative is to describe the experiences of someone coming to OpenZaurus for the first time.  Inevitably, a new user will come with assumptions that differ from those of the project\'s developers and his experiences of the installation may reveal things that need to be documented for all users.\n\nTherefore, I am trying to recount what I did so as to reveal the assumptions I started with.  I hope this will help to refine the installation documnetation.\n\nI have about 18 years experience of Unix; 12 of Linux.  I am a Debian developer and familiar with Debian\'s filesystem layout.  I am experienced with programming in BASIC, bash shell script, C, awk, sed, Perl, Eiffel and lately C++.  I once did some Z80 assembler programming.\n\n== System ==\n\nI set out to installOpenZaurus on a SL-C3100, which was previously running Zaurus\' native O/S.  My host computer runs Debian unstable.  It has \'\'\'dbus\'\'\' and \'\'\'hal\'\'\' installed rather than \'\'\'hotplug\'\'\'.\n\nI used 3.5.4.1-rc4, \'\'\'spitz\'\'\' version and selected the opie image, since the application I have already written is developed with Qtopia.\n\nI followed the instructions at [http://www.oesf.org/index.php?title=C3100_OpenZaurus].\n\nThere were no problems in repartitioning the C3100 and installing OpenZaurus on it. I got as far as making filesystems.  In order to make the VFAT filesystem on <tt>/dev/hda3</tt> \'\'(why does this need to be VFAT?)\'\' I had first to install \'\'\'dosfstools\'\'\', which in turn needed USB networking.\n\n== USB networking ==\n\nI had already got USB networking with the native Zaurus O/S.  This set-up does not work with OpenZaurus.\n\nFor the USB device to be recognised by the host computer, I had to load the \'\'\'usbnet\'\'\' and \'\'\'g_ether\'\'\' modules.  With these present, the following line was produced by <tt>lsusb</tt> on the host:\n\n <tt>Bus 003 Device 016: ID 0525:a4a2 Netchip Technology, Inc. Linux-USB Ethernet/RNDIS Gadget</tt>\n\nThe USB identity is <tt>0525:a4a2</tt> as opposed to <tt>04dd:9031</tt> for the native Zaurus O/S.  This meant changes to the hal configuration in <tt>/etc/hal/fdi/information/zaurus.fdi</tt> on the server, so that it would create the network interface <tt>usb0</tt>.\n\nI also needed to set up <tt>/etc/resolv.conf</tt> on the Z|aurus with the address of a nameserver.\n\nFinally I had to set up a default route; the gateway line in <tt>/etc/network/interfaces</tt> does not cause this to happen automatically:\n\n <tt>route add default gw 192.168.129.200</tt>\n\n== Continuing installation ==\n\nAt this point I was able to run \n\n <tt>ipkg update; ipkg upgrade; ipkg install dosfstools</tt>\n\nSince this was such a new release, nothing was upgraded.  I was now able to make the VFAT filesystem on <tt>/dev/hda3</tt>.\n\n\'\'\'Problem\'\'\': on installation, root does not have a home directory; <tt>/etc/passwd</tt> sets it to <tt>/home/root</tt>, but this directory does not exist.  I created it.\n\nI used <tt>adduser</tt> to create a personal login.\n\nI set a root password and set the system date using <tt>date -u</tt>.  The system does not seem to recognise <tt>Europe/London</tt> as a timezone.  It does recognise <tt>GMT1</tt>.\n\n== Installing Opie ==\n\nI now had a basic Linux system running.  Although I had loaded the opie tar image and chose <tt>1. Normal boot</tt> from the altboot prompt, I was not getting a graphical system; there is no reference to X in /etc/inittab and no indication of how to get it running.\n\nClearly, more research was needed...\n\nI used <tt>find</tt> to search the file system for files whose names include <tt>\'opie\'</tt>; there were almost none, so I concluded that I needed to install opie packages.  I searched for the main Opie site and discovered instructions for loading Familiar on an Ipaq; it seemed that these were inappropriate for a Zaurus and that I had to install specific packages.  So I did\n\n <tt>ipkg list | grep opie | sort -u | more</tt>\n\nto get a list of all opie-related packages; I had hoped to find a single \'\'\'task-opie\'\'\' package that would have installed as dependencies everything relevant, but there did not seem to be such a package.  So I installed some packages that looked as though they would be needed by my end users (we don\'t want our van drivers to be playing games on the Zaurus when they should be selling!)\n\nAt this point I switched to using ssh from my host computer; this made it a lot easier to read the screen and also to cut and paste between windows; typing on the Zaurus keyboard is a relatively slow job, particularly if you have big fingers!\n\nI continued by installing all the \'\'\'task-opie-*\'\'\' packages except for \'\'\'task-opie-games\'\'\' and \'\'\'task-opie-extra-games\'\'\'.  This had the desired effect of loading lots of opie packages.  However, something caused the main Zaurus console to go blank and unresponsive and I had to reboot it.  On rebooting, Opie started up, but with the screen oriented vertically; it did not respond to physically changing the screen position.  Set up Opie in response to prompts - the system is running as root, as shown by the prompt in a console, but it never asked for the root password, although opie-login is installed.\n\n\'\'The next day...\'\'\n\nI pursued the opie-login issue and discovered that you could configure it not to start up as root automatically.  However, that made it not start at all; a question to the Opie mailing list reveals that Qpe needs to be root for a lot of its functioning!  A bit of Windows mentality there, I think!  So I remove the opie-login package.\n\nAnother problem is the default keyboard mapping in Opie; in the Opie console, almost all the numbers and punctuation are mapped to letters and the KeyZ applet has no apparent effect.  I picked latin.xml in KeyZ and then noticed that latin appeared on the bottom of the creen as an option - choosing it gave me a good keyboard map; but why isn\'t it set to that in the first place?\n\nA third problem was that the screen always booted in tablet mode and did not rotate when I changed the physical rotation.  I discovered that one of the icons along the bottom did \"Enable rotation\" and with that turned on, rotation worked.\n\nDocumentation is a major issue, as is all too common with Open Source projects; the skeleton of the Opie manual is avaialble, but most entries have no content.\n\n== Trying to achieve automatic USB network connection ==\n\nI attempted to have the network come up automatically when the USB cable is plugged in.  First I added a file <tt>/etc/modutils/net</tt> containing:\n\n g_ether\n usbnet\n\nand added an executable script  <tt>/etc/network/if-up.d/setroute</tt> to establish a default route.  Unfortunately, this proved to be extremely flaky.  The <tt>g_ether</tt> and <tt>usbnet</tt> modules would be loaded at boot, but the connection would fail to be detected by the host computer and therefore it was impossible to establish the network connection.  I had to revert to a completely manual install after the USB was plugged in.  I saw somewhere that there is a problem with the USB connection after a suspend/resume; I wonder if this is a related problem?','utf-8');
