0 PST).\n\nNow, once a day at the time of least BerliOS traffic, your site should automatically pull all the changes from the master wiki and install them in its own database.\n\nIf you\'re having trouble getting the reports sent by mail, try one of these:\n* $HOME/ozdump/update-site 2>&1 | /usr/bin/mail user@example.com -s \'cron: wiki mirror updated\'\n* $HOME/ozdump/update-site 2>&1 | /usr/lib/sendmail user@example.com\n\nNow add a link to your mirror on [[Wiki Mirrors]].  Thanks for helping to preserve this data.\n\n== More Information ==\n\n=== Mirrors vs. Master Site ===\n\nVolatile data and data that is easily rebuilt is not stored in the dumpfile.  This makes each incremental changeset a lot smaller but does mean that the mirror isn\'t identical to the master wiki.\n\n* The mirror database is marked in the config file as read-only.\n* All user tables are dropped in order to keep passwords secret.  You can only browse the site on a mirror -- you can\'t log in.\n* The page counters are all zeroed.  If we didn\'t do this, we\'d get rows in the dumpfile every time someone so much as visits a page.  That\'s too much churn.\n* Each page is individually protected against edits.  This also hides the Edit tab.\n* The fulltext index is dropped.  It needs to be rebuilt each time you update the data on a mirror unless you don\'t want to support fulltext search.\n* Page history remains intact, but the Recent Changes link is empty.  You can rebuild the recent changes table if you want.\n\n=== Commands ===\n\nThese assume that you have a working php command-line executable.  Run php --version.\n\nRebuilds the text index:\n   php maintenance/rebuildtextindex.php\nFlushes the cache:\n   php maintenance/rebuildrecentchanges.php\n\n== Q&A ==\n\n; What\'s the difference between \"config\" file and \"SiteSettings.php\"? : SiteSettings contains the database information required to run the MediaWiki application.  It requires SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE and DELETE permissions.  config c